<LP>
   AMERICAN INTERNATIONAL is buying International Lease
Finance, an aircraft-leasing concern, for cash and stock
valued at about $1.3 billion. With a cash-rich insurer and
financial-services firm as its parent company, International
Lease may enjoy more flexibility in how it peddles its
portfolio of jetliners.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. is pursuing a plan to create a global radio
network to be run by government and industry. It would need a
$1 billion satellite system and a new generation of digital
radios. Opposition from broadcasters is likely.
   ---
   RJR Nabisco has budgeted $250 million in fees for its debt
refinancing, suggesting that patching up leveraged firms may
be the financial community's next big moneymaker.
   ---
   Siebe won an auction to buy Foxboro of Massachusetts for
$656.4 million. Shares of the British maker of control
devices tumbled amid concern that the purchase price is too
high.
   ---
   Bond prices dropped as investors worried about too many
issues coming to market. Stocks also fell, in part on some
bad earnings news. The Dow Jones industrials lost 12.13
points.
                                                                                                       

   Canada's financial markets recovered after an initial
sell-off yesterday following the demise of a constitutional
accord on Quebec's status.
   ---
   Gold prices rose after South Africa's central bank said it
actively supported the market in recent weeks.
   ---
   Thrift regulators issued rules on how much thrifts can pay
in dividends, in an effort to make S&amp;Ls more attractive to
investors.
   ---
   U.S. auto sales fell 3.6% in midJune from a year ago, as
the Big Three's slippage more than offset gains by Japanese
makers. But analysts said the figures suggest that the
current sales slump may be over.
   ---
   Chase Manhattan plans to slash expenses by at least $300
million, or 8%, over the next six to 12 months, and possibly
lay off 3,000 people.
   ---
   Trump's bankers raced to try to complete a $65 million
bailout of the developer by this morning and are expected to
provide interim financing.
   ---
   Caterpillar disclosed it expects "substantially lower"
earnings and flat sales this year. The company's stock
tumbled on the announcement.
   ---
   Michelin warned of possible losses and announced the
elimination of 2,260 jobs. The French tire maker's stock
plunged 8.3% on the news.
   ---
   Motorola and Hitachi agreed to hold talks in an attempt to
settle their computer-chip patent dispute.
   ---
   Armco expects a second-quarter loss and may omit its
dividend due to problems in its reinsurance business.
   ---
   Southern Co. units will receive $300 million before taxes
in a settlement with Gulf States Utilities of a dispute over
power sales contracts.
   ---
   Melville agreed to buy Imasco's Peoples unit for $330
million to create the fifth-largest U.S. drugstore chain.
